hod: if the method is a function in non-strict mode, null and undefined will be replaced with the global object, and primitive values will be boxed (converted to their wrapper objects).",[17,1144,1145,1146,1148,1149,1151],{},"That's why ",[21,1147,23],{}," ends up pointing to ",[21,1150,1073],{},", and why you see a constructor-wrapped value.",[12,1153,1155],{"id":1154},"strict-mode","Strict Mode",[17,1157,1158],{},"Now let's talk about what strict mode is.",[17,1160,1161],{},[1162,1163],"img",{"alt":1164,"src":1165},"Strict mode","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-01-10%2000.46.54.png",[17,1167,1168,1169,1173],{},"So what is strict mode? JavaScript is a pretty loose and forgiving language to develop in, which makes it easy to run into problems. Strict mode is there to stop us from hitting those situations — it keeps code that ",[1170,1171,1172],"em",{},"would"," cause problems from quietly running anyway.",[17,1175,1176],{},[1162,1177],{"alt":1178,"src":1179},"Strict mode explained","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-01-10%2000.48.19.png",[17,1181,1182,1183,1185,1186,1188,1189,39],{},"What's the main feature here? For example, if ",[21,1184,23],{}," would point to ",[21,1187,1073],{},", you get an error instead — a simple call ends up pointing to ",[21,1190,1067],{},[61,1192,1194],{"className":63,"code":1193,"language":65,"meta":66,"style":66},"'use strict'\n\nfunction fn () {\n  console.log(this); \u002F\u002F undefined\n}\n\nfn();\n",[21,1195,1196,1201,1205,1213,1228,1232,1236],{"__ignoreMap":66},[70,1197,1198],{"class":72,"line":73},[70,1199,1200],{"class":96},"'use strict'\n",[70,1202,1203],{"class":72,"line":90},[70,1204,110],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":109},[70,1206,1207,1209,1211],{"class":72,"line":100},[70,1208,116],